le delinquency to demonstrate how cultural discourses shape both the young and teenage girl in America. Although girls' culture has until now received comparatively little attention from scholars, this work confirms that understanding the culture of girls is essential to understanding how gender works in our society. Making a significant contribution to a long-neglected area of social and cultural inquiry, Delinquents and Debutantes will be of central interest to those in women's studies, American studies, history, literature, and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGirls in popular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aGirlszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aGirlszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aDevlin, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFormanek-Brunell, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Julia D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHubler, Angela E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInness, Sherrie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInness, Sherrie A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJustice-Malloy, Rhona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKearney, Mary Celeste, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcComb, Mary C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuiz, Vicki L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScanlon, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchrum, Kelly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTedesco, Laur